        "* Each time you run the Sinkhorn algorithm, you should use $\\epsilon = 0.1 \\cdot \\bar{C}$, with $\\bar{C} = \\frac{1}{nm} \\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^m C_{ij}$ is the mean of the cost matrix.  It remains to adapt the $\\epsilon$ value according to the cost matrix, to control the magnitude of the entries of $C / \\epsilon$. Why this strategy? What will happen if $\\epsilon$ is too small compared to the entries of $C$?\n",
